ovided for the `TaskManager.can_execute` method to handle circular dependencies.\n\n2. **Implement the Changes:**\n   - Replace the existing `add_task` method with the corrected version.\n   - Replace the existing `can_execute` method with the version that includes a check for circular dependencies.\n\n3. **Test the Changes:**\n   - Add test cases to ensure that the new implementation correctly handles task dependencies and circular dependencies.\n   - Ensure that the `add_task` method works as expected and tasks are added with their dependencies.\n\n4. **Document the Changes:**\n   - Update any relevant documentation to reflect the changes made.\n   - Provide comments in the code to explain the logic for handling dependencies and circular dependencies.\n\n5. **Prepare for Further Development:**\n   - Ensure that the code is in a state where it can be easily extended by Agent 2 to add missing functionality.\n   - Identify any areas where additional features can be integrated smoothly.\n\n### Revised Code Snippet\n\nHere is the revised `TaskManager` class with the suggested changes:\n\n```python\nclass TaskManager:\n    """Manages development tasks with dependencies. It helps in scheduling tasks and\n    ensuring that dependencies are met before a task is executed.\n    """\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.tasks = {}\n        self.dependencies = {}\n\n    def add_task(self, task_id, dependencies=None):\n        """Adds a task to the task manager.\n        :param task_id: str, unique identifier for the task\n        :param dependencies: list of str, list of task IDs that this task depends on\n        """\n        if dependencies is None:\n            dependencies = []\n        self.tasks[task_id] = False  # False indicates the task is not completed\n        self.dependencies[task_id] = dependencies\n\n    def complete_task(self, task_id):\n        """Marks a task as completed.\n        :param task_id: str, unique identifier for the task\n        """\n        if task_id in self.tasks:\n            self.tasks[task_id] = True\n        else:\n            print(f"Task {task_id} does not exist.")\n\n    def can_execute(self, task_id, visited=None):\n        """Checks if a task can be executed based on its dependencies.\n        :param task_id: str, unique identifier for the task\n        :param visited: set, set of visited task IDs to detect circular dependencies\n        :return: bool, True if the task can be executed, False otherwise\n        """\n        if visited is None:\n            visited = set()\n        if task_id in visited:\n            return False  # Circular dependency detected\n        visited.add(task_id)\n        if task_id not in self.dependencies:\n            return True\n        return all(self.can_execute(dep, visited) for dep in self.dependencies[task_id])\n```\n\n### Test Cases\n\nAdd test cases to verify the new implementation:\n\n```python\ndef test_add_task():\n    task_manager = TaskManager()\n    task_manager.add_task("task1")\n    assert task_manager.tasks["task1"] is False, "Task should be added as not completed"\n    assert task_manager.dependencies["task1"] == [], "Task should have no dependencies"\n\n    task_manager.add_task("task2", ["task1"])\n    assert task_manager.tasks["task2"] is False, "Task should be added as not completed"\n    assert task_manager.dependencies["task2"] == ["task1"], "Task should have the correct dependencies"\n\ndef test_can_execute_with_circular_dependency():\n    task_manager = TaskManager()\n    task_manager.add_task("task1", ["task2"])\n    task_manager.add_task("task2", ["task1"])\n    assert not task_manager.can_execute("task1"), "Circular dependency should be detected"\n\ndef test_can_execute_without_circular_dependency():\n    task_manager = TaskManager()\n    task_manager.add_task("task1", ["task2"])\n    task_manager.add_task("task2")\n    assert task_manager.can_execute("task2"), "Task with no dependencies should be executable"\n    assert not task_manager.can_execute("task1"), "Task with unmet dependency should not be executable"\n    task_manager.complete_task("task2")\n    assert task_manager.can_execute("task1"), "Task with met dependency should be executable"\n```\n\n### Documentation\n\nUpdate the documentation to reflect the changes:\n\n```python\nclass TaskManager:\n    """Manages development tasks with dependencies. It helps in scheduling tasks and\n    ensuring that dependencies are met before a task is executed.\n    """\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.tasks = {}\n        self.dependencies = {}\n\n    def add_task(self, task_id, dependencies=None):\n        """Adds a task to the task manager.\n        :param task_id: str, unique identifier for the task\n        :param dependencies: list of str, list of task IDs that this task depends on\n        """\n        if dependencies is None:\n            dependencies = []\n        self.tasks[task_id] = False  # False indicates the task is not completed\n        self.dependencies[task_id] = dependencies\n        # This method adds a task to the task manager with its dependencies.\n        # If no dependencies are provided, it initializes an empty list.\n\n    def complete_task(self, task_id):\n        """Marks a task as completed.\n        :param task_id: str, unique identifier for the task\n        """\n        if task_id in self.tasks:\n            self.tasks[task_id] = True\n        else:\n            print(f"Task {task_id} does not exist.")\n        # This method marks a task as completed if it exists in the task manager.\n\n    def can_execute(self, task_id, visited=None):\n        """Checks if a task can be executed based on its dependencies.\n        :param task_id: str, unique identifier for the task\n        :param visited: set, set of visited task IDs to detect circular dependencies\n        :return: bool, True if the task can be executed, False otherwise\n        """\n        if visited is None:\n            visited = set()\n        if task_id in 